<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <partial src="partials/headcontent_better.html"/>
    <title>Evening Forest</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div class="dark">
      <partial src="partials/header.html"/>
    </div>
    <div class="parallax p_forest"></div>
    <div class="container forest dark">
      <div class="row content headliner d-flex">
        <i class="background"></i>
        <div class="col-lg-12 align-self-center">
          <h2>Evening Forest</h2>
          <hr>
          <p class="work-types">
            <span>Unreal Engine 4</span>
            <span>â€¢</span>
            <span>Maya</span>
          </p>
          <div class="text-block">
            <p>Lets do something zen. I wanted to experiment with color scheming and particle effects in Unreal Engine 4. A forest at the crest of dusk seemed perfect for creating a beautiful color palate.</p>
            <p>But this kinda project is one better seen. Take a look at the render below.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="row content videoWrapper">
        <i class="background"></i>
        <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/ZiHittWYRxU?ecver=1" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>
      </div>
      <div class="row content">
        <i class="background"></i>
        <div class="col-lg-12">
            <h2>I started with a color scheme</h2>
            <div class="text-block">
              <img src="resources/forest/colors.png" alt="">
              <p>I built this scene from an initial color scheme. After scouring some color reference sites and playing around with some combinations, I decided on the above, offering a dark, yet vibrant pallet to draw from.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="row content" style="height:800px">
        <i class="background parallax p_forest_artboard"></i>
        <div class="col-lg-12">
              <h2 style="background-color: rgba(0,0,0,.8); padding: 10px">My Inspiration Board</h2>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="row content">
        <i class="background"></i>
        <div class="col-lg-12">
          <h2>A desire to explore</h2>
          <div class="text-block">
            <p>A good scene is structured in a way that leads your eyes through it. This can be accomplished with color, light, geometry, or implied motion (in this case, actual motion).</p>
            <p>I wanted to instill in the viewer the desire to move into and beyond the presented scene; an urge to explore. In the context of a videogame, this desire is doubly important.</p>
            <p>Because of this, all elements in this scene are designed to draw the viewer inward.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="row content threes d-flex">
        <i class="background"></i>
        <div class="col-lg-4">
          <h2>Color</h2>
          <div class="text-block">
              <p>The colors transition from a cool deep blue at the edges to a warm pink in the center. This draws the eye through the scene into the middle, but so far this only implied two dimensional movement. We need somthing else</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-lg-4">
          <h2>Geometry</h2>
          <div class="text-block">
            <p>The trunks of the trees are likely the first element of the scene the viewer notices. These draw the eye down, reaching and following the horizontal span of grass extending neatly to the center, while the fog implies depth. Cattails draw the eye upwards if viewed from the bottom.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-lg-4">
          <h2>Movement</h2>
          <div class="text-block">
          <p>Subtle, but an essential detail. Moving elements draw you mentally into the scene. Fireflies drift into the forest, giving the viewer's eye a clear element to follow inwards. Ripples in the pond reinforce the critical path. All other movement sells the scene as a living place.</p>
        </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <partial src="partials/footer.html"/>
  </body>
</html>
